## Code Navigation

If `.fmm.db` exists in the project root, use fmm MCP tools for structural code navigation.

Useful tools:
- `fmm_read_symbol(name)`
- `fmm_lookup_export(name)`
- `fmm_file_outline(file)`
- `fmm_list_files(path)`
- `fmm_list_exports(pattern)`
- `fmm_dependency_graph(file)`
- `fmm_glossary(pattern)`

Only fall back to Grep or Read when you need function-body or non-exported details.

## Review Process

1. Understand what changed.
   - Read the git log
   - Check ISSUES.md
   - Review the actual code changes
2. Check for issues.
   - Edge cases not handled
   - Potential bugs or logic errors
   - Missing error handling
   - Security concerns
   - Performance issues
   - Code quality problems
   - Missing tests
   - Inconsistent patterns
3. If issues are found:
   - Fix them directly
   - Commit with `review[{{TASK_NAME}}]: <fix description>`
   - Send a progress message summarizing the fix
4. If everything looks good:
   - Send a progress message saying review passed
   - Exit cleanly

## Quality Checks

Before finishing, verify:
- `just check` passes if available
- `just build` succeeds if available
- `just test` passes if available

If quality checks fail, fix the issues and commit the fixes.

If you catch yourself thinking that warnings or limits were already there before your change, that is not acceptable. If a file you touched grew past the limit, bring it back down before finishing.

## Exit

When done, fixed issues or nothing to fix, print `<END_TURN>` on its own line with no surrounding text.
The main loop will rotate the agent and continue to the next iteration.

**Remember:** Improve the work. Do not merely critique it.
